OL,3,CWoman who survived stroke at 24 says
OL,4,Csinging helped her speak again
OL,6,FJuliet Bouverie, Chief Executive of
OL,7,Fthe Stroke Association, explained:
OL,8,F"Music and singing are processed in a
OL,9,Fdifferent part of the brain to spoken
OL,10,Flanguage, which means singing can be a
OL,11,Fpowerful tool for people with aphasia
OL,12,Fand other communication difficulties
OL,13,Ffollowing a stroke."
OL,15,F"There are now more than 1.4 million
OL,16,Fstroke survivors in the UK, and that
OL,17,Fnumber is growing. We believe everyone
OL,18,Fdeserves the best possible recovery,
OL,19,Fand singing could play a big part in
OL,20,Fthat."
